(40, 19, 10, 20, 18, 22, 22, NULL, 'Marriage and Favor from God', 'This connection highlights the contrasting views on marriage. While Matthew 19:10 suggests that marriage may be burdensome, Proverbs 18:22 emphasizes that finding a wife is a good thing and brings favor from the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 10, 46, 7, 1, 2, 'it is not good to marry', 'Marriage and Its Challenges', 'Both passages emphasize the difficulties of marriage, with Matthew highlighting the disciples'' reluctance to marry and 1 Corinthians suggesting it is good to avoid relationships unless necessary. This connection highlights the tension between the ideal of celibacy and the practical need for marriage to avoid immorality.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 10, 54, 4, 3, 3, 'not good to marry', 'Marriage and Abstinence Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the challenges and restrictions surrounding marriage. Matthew 19:10 reflects the disciples'' concern about the difficulties of marriage, while 1 Timothy 4:3 discusses forbidding marriage as a command, highlighting a similar theme of abstinence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 10, 54, 5, 11, 15, 'it is not good to marry', 'Marriage and Faithfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the challenges of marriage and the implications for faithfulness. Matthew 19:10 reflects the disciples'' concern about the difficulties of marriage, while 1 Timothy 5:11-15 warns against younger widows marrying and neglecting their faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 10, 1, 2, 18, 18, 'it is not good to marry', 'Marriage and Loneliness Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of companionship in both passages. Matthew 19:10 reflects the disciples'' concern about marriage, while Genesis 2:18 emphasizes that it is not good for man to be alone.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 11, 46, 7, 17, 17, 'to whom it is given', 'Divine Calling and Individual Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of individual calling and the unique gifts given to each person. Both passages emphasize that not everyone can accept certain teachings or roles, as they are distributed according to God''s design.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 11, 40, 13, 11, 11, 'save they to whom it is given', 'Understanding Divine Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize that knowledge of spiritual truths is selectively given. Matthew 19:11 states that not all can receive certain teachings, while Matthew 13:11 indicates that understanding the mysteries of the kingdom is granted to some but not others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 11, 46, 7, 2, 2, NULL, 'Marriage and Celibacy Discussion', 'This connection highlights the theme of marital relationships and celibacy. Matthew 19:11 discusses the ability to accept a certain teaching, while 1 Corinthians 7:2 emphasizes the necessity of marriage to avoid fornication.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 11, 46, 7, 7, 9, 'All men cannot receive this saying', 'Connection on Gifts and Celibacy', 'Both passages emphasize that not everyone can accept the call to celibacy, as it is a gift given to some. Matthew highlights that ''all men cannot receive this saying,'' while Paul acknowledges that ''every man hath his proper gift of God.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 11, 46, 7, 35, 35, 'All men cannot receive this saying', 'Focus on Spiritual Commitment', 'This connection highlights the idea that not everyone can embrace a life of celibacy or singleness, as noted in Matthew 19:11. Similarly, 1 Corinthians 7:35 emphasizes attending to the Lord without distraction, suggesting a focus on spiritual matters over worldly concerns.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 12, 46, 7, 32, 38, 'eunuchs for the kingdom of heaven's sake', 'Eunuchs and Unmarried Life', 'Both passages emphasize the value of remaining unmarried for spiritual devotion. Matthew discusses eunuchs for the kingdom of heaven, while 1 Corinthians highlights the advantages of the unmarried in serving the Lord without distraction.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 12, 46, 9, 5, 5, 'made themselves eunuchs for the kingdom of heaven's sake', 'Eunuchs and Apostolic Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of personal choice regarding marital status for the sake of ministry. Matthew discusses those who have made themselves eunuchs for the kingdom, while 1 Corinthians addresses the authority of apostles regarding marriage.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 12, 23, 56, 3, 4, 'eunuchs for the kingdom of heaven's sake', 'Eunuchs and God''s Covenant', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of eunuchs in God''s plan. Matthew highlights different types of eunuchs, while Isaiah reassures eunuchs of their value in keeping God''s covenant.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 12, 23, 39, 7, 7, 'eunuchs', 'Eunuchs in Biblical Context', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of eunuchs, highlighting their roles and conditions. Matthew discusses eunuchs for the kingdom of heaven, while Isaiah mentions eunuchs in the palace of Babylon.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
